This was the hardest design tension of the session.

On one side: make the tool useful. doctor that checks doc drift.
gaps that shows uncovered files. preflight that verifies session
hygiene. Every feature request from dogfooding pulled toward more
opinion in the tool.

On the other: keep the tool minimal. Kinds are just strings. Edge
types are open vocabulary. The tool reads and writes a graph. It
doesn't know what 'good' looks like — YOU define good through the
notes you write (constraints, values, warnings).

Where we landed: the tool provides primitives (note, read, follow,
refs, context, find, kinds, doctor, branch). Doctor reports graph
state as facts. Everything above that — doc drift checks, tested-by
coverage, session hygiene — belongs in the repo's own test suite
or in notes, not in the tool.

This means: adopting mycelium doesn't impose a workflow. You bring
your own culture. The tool carries it. The skill shows patterns.
But the tool never tells you you're doing it wrong.
